value.Title: Psychopharmacology
value.Description: Psychopharmacology broadly refers to the scientific study of how pharmacological agents affect brain function and behavior.  This course will cover core pharmacology concepts and principles, such as neurotransmitters, receptors, drug classes, and mechanisms of drug action, while highlighting recent findings related to pharmacogenetics and sex/gender differences in psychopharmacology.  There will also be a primary focus on drug therapy for major psychiatric disorders, including addiction, depression, anxiety disorders, and schizophrenia.

value.Title: Augmenting Human Cognition
value.Description: Can you make yourself smarter? What can be done to limit the age-related decline in certain cognitive processes? Does relying on technology ultimately help or hurt human performance? In this course, we will discuss some of the many different ways that researchers have tried to improve cognition (brain training, exercise, nutrition, pharmaceuticals, augmented reality), and critically evaluate how successful these endeavors have been. The course will require reading and discussion, and the main project will be a review paper that the students will co-author with the instructor for submission as a manuscript.

value.Title: Science Of Happiness
value.Description: Individuals and societies are increasingly interested in the concept of happiness. This course seeks to provide a psychological account of happiness - its definition, determinants, and outcomes. We address questions such as: How do we go about measuring happiness? This course will engage and challenge students not only intellectually, but also experientially as we work on enhancing happiness in our lives and in the lives of others around us.

value.Title: Parapsyc & Psychic Claims
value.Description: Prerequisites:  PSY 12000 and PSY 20100, or equivalent.  Analysis of Parapsychological and Psychic Claims. Course will survey current research and views regarding parapsychological and psychic phenomena – such as extrasensory perception, mental telepathy, and clairvoyance – and related phenomena involving the paranormal more generally defined.  We will evaluate the arguments and evidence for and against various claims concerning these phenomena in terms of theoretical and methodological issues.  The major concern is whether parapsychological phenomena can be evaluated using the scientific method and, if so, what can be concluded from the research to date?  You will learn about not only parapsychological phenomena and the views of advocates and skeptics, but also the nature of science, research design and statistics, and psychological processes involved in cognition, emotion, and belief.

value.Title: Psychology Of Gender
value.Description: Prerequisite PSY20300 and PSY24000 - PSY39200, Psychology of Gender This course will cover how gender affects the experiences and lives of all people. Covering classic theories as well as the latest research on gender, topics will include: What is gender and (how) is it different from biological sex? What are gender stereotypes, where do they come from, and why are they harmful? These questions will be examined broadly as well as within specific domains such as gender in the workplace, gender and sexuality, and gender and in childhood. Students will be expected to actively engage in discussions about these topics, their practical implications, and potential solutions. Students will also learn to critically engage with psychological research on gender and how it can reinforce systems of inequality, for example by treating gender as a binary variable or ignoring the experiences of individuals with multiple intersecting identities (e.g., Black or lesbian women).

value.Title: Seminar:Genes, Brain & Bhavr
value.Description: Course examines how genes regulate development and function of the brain to ultimately influence behavior. Goal is to provide students with the background needed to understand and think critically about the genetic components of Neuroscience and behavioral research. Questions explored will include: What are chromosomes and genes? What do they do? How do they do it? How do genes control development of the brain? How are single genes manipulated in animals to study their effects on behavior? How can genes associated with normal or abnormal behavior be identified? What is epigenetics? What role does it play in behavioral genetics? What has been learned from gene-behavior studies in animals? in humans? What do these studies tell us about the nature-nurture controversy? Many behaviors could be used to explore the principles these questions address.

value.Title: Neuroethics
value.Description: Neuroscience research has led to a better understanding of the neuronal basis of human behavior. This knowledge, together with new technological approaches that can predict and even control some aspects of human behavior, can have a major impact on social policy. The course explores ethical, social, and legal implications of the use of new technological and pharmacological advances in brain research.

value.Title: Seminar In Genes & Behavior
value.Description: This course examines how genes influence behavior. Several questions will be explored mainly through discussion of research and review papers. These will include:  What are chromosomes and genes and what do they do? How can genes associated with normal (e.g. IQ) or abnormal (e.g. schizophrenia) behavior be identified? How are single genes manipulated to study their effects on behavior? How are complex behaviors that depend on many genes studied? What has been learned from gene-behavior studies in animals and humans? Topics selected from:  learning & memory, mental illness, sexual orientation and drug & alcohol addiction What do these studies tell us about the nature-nurture controversy? Can behavior change gene function (e.g., epigenetics)?

value.Title: Open Science Practices In Psy
value.Description: This course provides an in-depth introduction to Open Science Practices which call for transparency at all stages of the research process. The course begins examining replication issues in psychology and other fields--documenting these problems and discussing the factors that cause such problems. The course then moves to discuss specific Open Science Practices designed to address these problems, including preregistration, Registered Reports, making code and materials available, and data sharing.
